05670nam a22009255i 9780812201598DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013940883  a97808122015987 a10.9783/97808122015982doi  a(DE-B1597)449011  a(OCoLC)979577789  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS554.83.N86bC47 2010 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a959.604/22221 aChon, Gina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBehind the Killing Fields :bA Khmer Rouge Leader and One of His Victims /cGina Chon, Sambath Thet. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (212 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Faceless Father -- t3. The New World Order -- t4. The Lost Childhood -- t5. The Vietnam Factor -- t6. The Missing Brother -- t7. The Enemies -- t8. The Year Zero -- t9. The Implosion -- t10. The Rebuilding -- t11. The Homecoming -- t12. The Understanding -- t13. The Killing Fields -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent history, atrocities have often been committed in the name of lofty ideals. One of the most disturbing examples took place in Cambodia's Killing Fields, where tens of thousands of victims were executed and hastily disposed of by Khmer Rouge cadres. Nearly thirty years after these bloody purges, two journalists entered the jungles of Cambodia to uncover secrets still buried there.Based on more than 1,000 hours of interviews with the top surviving Khmer Rouge leader, Nuon Chea, Behind the Killing Fields follows the journey of a man who began as a dedicated freedom fighter and wound up accused of crimes against humanity. Known as Brother Number 2, Chea was Pol Pot's top lieutenant. He is now in prison, facing prosecution in a United Nations-Cambodian tribunal for his actions during the Khmer Rouge rule, when more than two million Cambodians died. The book traces how the seeds of the Killing Fields were sown and what led one man to believe that mass killing was necessary for the greater good.Coauthor Sambath Thet, a Khmer Rouge survivor, shares his personal perspectives on the murderous regime and how some victims have managed to rebuild their lives. The stories of Nuon Chea and Sambath Thet collide when the two meet. While Thet holds Chea responsible for the death of his parents and brother, he strives for understanding over revenge in order to reveal the forces that destroyed his homeland in the name of creating utopia.In this age of suicide bombers and terror alerts, the world is still at a loss to comprehend the violence of zealots. Behind the Killing Fields bravely confronts this challenge in an exclusive portrait of one man's political madness and another's personal wisdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGenocidezCambodia. 0aPolitical atrocitieszCambodia. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aAutobiography.  aBiography.  aHistory.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aThet, Sambath, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsyl